               <msContents>
                  <summary>
                     <title>Mūshnāmah</title> (Book of the Mouse) or <title>Mūsh va Gurbah</title>
                     (Mouse and Cat), a mock-epic attributed to ‘Ubayd Zākānī (d. ca. 1370). A
                     mock-epic, attributed to ʻUbayd Zākānī,
                     it features a satirical fable concerning a cruel and hypocritical tyrant,
                     symbolically depicted as an evil cat, often associated with the founder of the
                     Muzzafarid Dynasty (1314–1393) <persName role="subject" key="person_f6542">Mubāriz
                        al-Dīn Muḥammad (r. 1314–1358)</persName>, who repeatedly torments a
                     community of virtuous mice. In the
                     tale, the tyrant is symbolically represented as an evil cat that torments a
                     community of virtuous mice. While this finely transcribed, and whimsically
                     illustrated manuscript lacks a colophon, the style suggests that the commercial
                     atelier (<hi rend="italic">muṣavvirkhānah</hi>) of painter <persName role="art"
                        cert="medium">Faqīr Chand (ca. 1790–1865)</persName>, or his son <persName key="person_f6875"
                        role="art" cert="medium">Shīvā Lāl (1817–1887)</persName>, known as <addName
                        type="epithet">Shāhī Muṣavvir</addName> (Royal Painter) illustrated
                     it.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_30-item1">
                     <author role="att" key="person_50025161" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/50025161"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard" role="att">‘Ubayd Zākānī, Niẓām
                           al-Dīn</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">عبيد زاكاني، نظام الدين</persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor role="art" cert="medium"><persName>Faqīr Chand (ca.
                           1790–1865)</persName></editor>
                     <editor role="art" cert="medium"><persName key="person_f6875">Shīvā Lāl
                        (1817–1887)</persName></editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_6427">Mūsh va Gurba</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_6427">Mūshnāmah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="alt" key="work_6427">Mouse and Cat</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_6427">موش و گربه</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" type="alt" key="work_6427">موشنامه</title>
                     <title type="alt" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_6427" change="#ids-cleanup"
                        >Qiṣṣah-'i Mūsh va Gurbah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_6427"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">Qiṣṣah-'i Gurbah va Mūsh</title>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="desc" key="work_6427" change="#ids-cleanup">Fable
                        of the mouse and the cat (masnavī poem)</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmalla"><locus from="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> ای خردمند عاقل ودانا * قصۀ موش وگربه برخوانا</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="11b"> برگ ۱۱پ (folio 11b):</locus> هست این
                        قصۀ عجیب وغریب * یادگار عبید زاکانا</explicit>
                     <colophon>No colophon, but former owner <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           key="person_f6443">John Bardoe Elliott</persName>'s inscription on the
                           <locus from="ib" to="ib">first right flyleaf b side (f. ib)</locus> in
                           <date calendar="#Gregorian">1846</date> both establishes terminus ante
                        quem and suggests the locus of production for the volume's
                        completion.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>Translated into English numerous times, including by Mas'ūd-i Farzād,
                        Omar Pound, and most recently by Hasan Javadi in an unpublished whimsical
                        metrical version.</note>
                     <colophon>No colophon</colophon>
                  </msItem>
